.NET Framework 3.5.name: VRTK_HeadsetFade
.NET Framework 3.5.summary: The purpose of the Headset Fade is to change the colour of the headset view to a specified colour over a given duration and to also unfade it back to being transparent.
.NET Framework 3.5.remarks: The Fade and Unfade methods can only be called via another script and this Headset Fade script does not do anything on initialisation to fade or unfade the headset view.
.NET Framework 3.5.example: VRTK/Examples/011_Camera_HeadSetCollisionFading has collidable walls around the play area and if the user puts their head into any of the walls then the headset will fade to black.

methods.name: Fade(Color color, float duration)
methods.summary: The Fade method initiates a change in the colour of the headset view to the given colour over a given duration.

params.value: The colour to fade the headset view to.
The time in seconds to take to complete the fade transition.

methods.name: FadeComplete()
IsFaded()
methods.summary: The IsFaded method returns true if the headset is currently fading or has completely faded and returns false if it is completely unfaded.
methods.returns: Returns true if the headset is currently fading or faded.

methods.name: IsTransitioning()
methods.summary: The IsTransitioning method returns true if the headset is currently fading or unfading and returns false if it is completely faded or unfaded.
methods.returns: Returns true if the headset is currently in the process of fading or unfading.

events.name: HeadsetFadeComplete
events.summary: Emitted when the user's headset has completed the fade and is now fully at the given colour.

events.name: HeadsetFadeStart
events.summary: Emitted when the user's headset begins to fade to a given colour.

events.name: HeadsetUnfadeComplete
events.summary: Emitted when the user's headset has completed unfading and is now fully transparent again.

events.name: HeadsetUnfadeStart
